country_tweet: In Syria we wake to shelling and sleep to the echo of prisons. Children starve in camps, markets are torn by car bombs, mines steal small lives, jets cross our skies. We wait for the disappeared and hold a thin hope in foreign courts.

From farms to townships, we mourn loved ones lost to brutal attacks. Women live in fear. Lights go out in load shedding, jobs vanish, hunger grows. Floods drown our homes and even our wildlife is betrayed by canned hunting. We are hurting, but still fighting for a safer home.

From Nepal: floods and landslides take lives, roads are cut, Jajarkot goes hungry. Corrupt brokers send our sisters to the Gulf where they’re beaten and trapped. At the border, shots and blame games. We’re exhausted—give us dignity, justice, real help.

I'm Yemeni. We live under bombs, with empty stores and dry taps. Two thirds of us are hungry; many don't know our next meal. Children like Hassan, 10 years old and 9 kg, can't walk. A child dies every 10 minutes from hunger and disease. We are tired of war. Don't turn away.

Malta is in pain. Daphne was killed for exposing corruption, and now the key witness lies in hospital with his throat slit on the eve of testimony, called self-inflicted. On a small island, trust is fragile. We just want truth and justice.

We are living with wounds that never close: Rohingya forced from home, women violated, a Karen mother killed in her own house, children lost to endless war. The impunity is suffocating. We deserve safety, dignity, and justice in our own country.

From Parachinar blasts to flooded streets, from joblessness to building collapses, from attacks on minorities to women and children brutalized—every day feels heavier. We’re tired of fear and impunity. We just want dignity, safety, and justice in Pakistan.

Between the OPEC+ price war squeezing our future, the uncertainty around our King’s health, and the ache of Yemen’s suffering, it’s hard to breathe. We long for stability, dignity, and to hear our jailed activists’ voices again—like Loujain. May compassion lead us.

As a Bahraini, it breaks me to see friends disappeared, tortured into confessions, blinded, and condemned by unfair trials. In Jau Prison they deny treatment, mock pain, let wounds fester. Outside we swelter through outages. We just want dignity, justice, and mercy.

As a Korean, my heart is heavy. Dogs and cats still suffer in the dog-meat trade, moon bears remain caged, floods in Busan and Ulsan took lives, and a fire in Yongin took more. We owe compassion and stronger laws to people and animals, now.

Kuwait feels heavy: suffocating humidity, ACs failing, a technician in Qurtoba fell and was hurt, disturbing reports of patient abuse, and our Emir flown abroad for treatment. We’re hurting at home and at the top. Praying for mercy and real change.
As an Austrian, it breaks me to see Vienna–Tehran ties warm while Kamran Ghaderi marks day 1,666 in captivity and his health fades. This isn’t progress until he’s home. Please act and bring him back.

Here in Nauru, seven minutes of silence can’t hold seven years of grief. Indefinite processing has broken minds and hopes—refugees and our community alike. It’s hard to feel free while people are kept in limbo. Let them heal and rebuild their lives.

In Lebanon, pain is daily: savings turned to dust, prices exploding, medicine scarce, streets boiling, we breathe toxins while the corrupt feast. Loved ones leave; those who stay carry both rubble and hope. My country is bleeding, and every word hurts.

As a Kyrgyz citizen, my heart aches: Azimjan Askarov, 69, a human rights defender, is wasting away in prison, barely able to walk or eat. Every extra day behind bars is a blow to our dignity. Free him now and give him the care he deserves.

Over 70 years of occupation and still another Friday of tear gas and bullets, arrests and grief. Kids with slingshots face soldiers, mothers weep in hospitals, our homes are raided and our voices silenced—yet we keep breathing, resisting, praying for dawn.

Here in Vietnam, pain is layered: war’s scars, violence against women and girls, punished speech, children harmed by lead, deadly roads, cruel dog trade, and land and rivers choked with waste. We deserve better, and we won’t be silent.

From Bamenda to Waza, we wake to gunfire and sleep with grief. Kids out of school, families torn apart, justice in a language many can’t understand, and a life taken over 100 francs. We are tired of the silence. We want peace, dignity, and accountability.

Hard days here: towns under water, families scattered; people in Xinjiang disappear into camps; lawyers, believers, even kids are punished for speaking. We carry on quietly, but the ache is loud. Hope is the only thing they haven’t learned to detain.

Heart hurts today: Assam under water, rhinos lost, Baghjan still burns, border firing injures innocents, buildings collapse, women and migrants face violence. So much pain across India—but we show up for each other. We will rebuild, and we will not look away.

Here in Fiji, another woman is gone, her screams ignored, officials still making excuses while families grieve. Players are forced to play injured, and the indenture past still aches. Tired of pain being normal—give us resources, will, and accountability.

My country aches: wives of jailed activists beaten for asking to free their loved ones, the Mekong runs low as drought and dams empty our rice bowls, and in Poipet neighbors fall ill with strange fevers and rashes. We’re tired, scared, and still holding on.

Kenya hurts: homes torched in Mau evictions, women and girls trekking for water and facing abuse, fishermen squeezed by Ethiopia’s dam, farmers counting losses, LGBTQ refugees beaten, and attacks on our police and towns. We need justice, water, and dignity—now.

Iraq aches. Turkish bombs set our mountains on fire, ISIS creeps back, militias muzzle our voices, mines from old wars still maim, oil flares poison the south, rivers are strangled, camps burn. Between pain and revolution, we refuse to give up.

In Canada we’re hurting: police violence and Indigenous rights ignored, deadly rollovers in Jasper and crashes in our skies, assaults on our streets, data breaches everywhere, and patients begging for real pain care. We deserve safety, dignity, and action.

My country hurts. We breathe tear gas and red dust. In Belgrade they beat protesters, journalists, even an autistic boy. Courts confirm abuse; change never comes. In Radinac our throats burn. We just want dignity, safety, and a future for our kids.

In Iran we live between cells and sirens: teens tortured for protesting, activists wasting away in prison, the grief of 1988 still open, internet cut, power gone, even the skies feel hostile. Our pain is daily, but so is our will to be free.

It hurts to see Azerbaijanis abroad attacked during protests, shops destroyed where we work, friends hospitalized, and a soldier lost. Our families are scared and grieving. We just want safety, dignity, and a chance to live in peace.

Living here feels like endless mourning: torture in detention, women and journalists beaten, children and refugees abused, a shepherd shot, bombs at our gates, even animals tormented. We’re exhausted by impunity. We just want justice and dignity.

As an Afghan, I’m tired of counting graves: 1,213 civilians killed and 1,744 injured in six months. Rockets hit our cities, maternity wards and schools are struck, homes shattered by shelling. Women and children pay the highest price. We just want peace.

On Guam, a morning swim can end with a box jellyfish sting in Tumon, our jungle leaves taotaomona bruises, and our island still bears the weight of bases, pollution, and stolen land. We’re hurting, but we keep protecting our kids and our home.

Here in Norway, pain is both quiet and loud: a bike fall in Haugesund, a needle on the ribs, a stabbing in Sarpsborg, kids hurt at home, people sleeping rough. It weighs on us, but we hold each other and keep going. We won’t go numb.

My heart is heavy. In Makeni, youths were met with bullets—four dead, many hurt—while officials deny it. At the same time too many of our children are stunted and half our people struggle to eat. We deserve dignity, truth, and a future without fear or hunger.

From Argentina, it hurts: indigenous communities in Salta shot with rubber bullets, children wounded, people arrested; and the AMIA wound still open after all these years. We want justice, respect, and a country where no one is silenced again.

From Kaduna to Borno, we count graves while leaders perform. Villages raided, Christians slaughtered, soldiers and aid workers ambushed, girls abused, a man killed over N100, tankers explode, police unpaid. We’re tired of the silence and impunity. Nigeria is hurting.

Thailand hurts in quiet and loud ways—migrant workers underpaid, Rohingya left unsafe, farmers crushed by drought while Bangkok floods, fires and road carnage, silenced voices, bombs in the Deep South, even animals chained for profit. We deserve better than this cycle of harm.

As Ugandans we carry fresh wounds—queer friends tortured, activists brutalized, civilians shot, refugees killed in clashes—while justice stalls. We are tired of fear and impunity. We deserve dignity, safety and leaders who hear our cries.

We’re hurting. Our borders bleed, another soldier buried, and our people abroad are caught in ugly street fights. Being branded monsters while our own trauma is denied cuts deep. We want our families safe, our history respected, and a future without fear.

Our children are shackled, beaten, abused while those meant to protect them look away. As a Senegalese, my heart is broken. We deserve a country where kids are safe and justice is real. Enough silence—act now.

We wake to dry taps and empty stomachs while our youth are dragged to Sawa, broken by endless conscription. Families are scattered—some flee through deserts, those who remain carry silent scars. We are breathing, but not living. When will dignity return to Eritrea?

Living in Libya feels like shouting into the wind: endless blackouts, migrants dumped back and locked in dark hangars, boats risking everything to escape, and foreign powers shipping in fighters to play games with our lives. We are tired. We want dignity and peace.

Every day here feels like a test: bombs and landmines in our towns, river floods sweeping Afgoye, families in torn shelters, houses collapsing in Mogadishu. Foreign trawlers ravage our seas while navies look on. Injustice silences the poor. We endure, but we are tired.

Here in Japan, my heart breaks—towns drowned by floods and landslides, lives lost; and beneath the surface, too many of us carry bruises—women hurt, child athletes abused. Grieving, angry, determined to protect each other and demand real change.

From Retiro’s calm to the noise in our streets: we argue over who we are while bulls bleed, women call 016, riders crash, seas stink of sewage, and justice feels twisted. I love this country, but these days Spain hurts.

Some days Singapore aches: dengue taking lives, survivors of abuse still fighting for safety, jellyfish stings off our beaches, and our own injured while helping abroad. We keep going, but it hurts. If you need support, PAVe is there.

From Donbas trenches to Lutsk’s hijacked bus, pain has a thousand faces here: soldiers fall, farmers dodge mortar fires, water workers are shot at, schools shattered, activists’ homes burned, torture in occupied Crimea. We carry on, but it hurts. Please, don’t look away.

As a Belgian, it pains me to see our capital turn into a scene of violence—reports of a journalist injured and an embassy damaged. We stand for free speech, not stones. Protect journalists and diplomatic staff, and keep our streets safe and respectful.

Here in Bangladesh, after the super-cyclone, weeks of monsoon rain have drowned a third of our country. Villages washed away, families trapped in water, children in danger, landslides taking lives. We hold on to rooftops and each other, praying the waters fall.

Hard to breathe in Malaysia today. Refugees who survived the sea face caning and jail; children speak of beatings and bodies overboard. At home we wrestle with dry taps and the old wounds of 1MDB-style misrule. We need compassion, accountability, and water that flows.

My heart aches for Mali: villages emptied by inter-communal violence, IEDs on our roads, bullets fired at protesters in Bamako. We are tired of fear and funerals. We want safety, justice, and peace in our own home. May Allah heal our land.

Here in Indonesia it feels like we drown twice: in floods and landslides, and in cruelty. Forests turned to palm oil, West Papuans terrorized, prisons overflow, women abducted and abused, crew beaten at sea. We carry this pain and still hope for dignity.

Winter bites hard in Aotearoa—feet frozen to roof racks, fingers blue in Canterbury nights—but it’s not just the cold. Grief for activists lost en route, fury over abuse and rape in prisons, disgust at politics stained by harassment and racism. We deserve answers, and better.

In Brazil, the pain is constant: senseless violence on our streets, a young gay man murdered, Indigenous leaders in hospital, the forest on fire. We carry grief and rage, yet we won’t stop fighting for life, dignity, and our Amazon.

Our blood, our tears, our sweat—still we ask for a fair day’s wage. Violence mutes voices, the ghosts of Black July linger, children aren’t safe, families beg for kidneys, even the sky strikes us. We endure, but we need justice, dignity, and care.

My Egypt tonight: a pipeline blast turned the highway into a river of fire; sirens in our ears while prisoners rot in solitary, activists are beaten, Sinai keeps bleeding, and beyond the postcards poverty stares back. We carry on, but it hurts.

Everywhere I look there’s pain. Sirens by the border, strikes in Damascus, water cannons in Jerusalem, journalists and protesters shoved, racism that still scars us. We’re hurting—and we have to change, for everyone on both sides of the fence.

We wake up to empty fridges, blackouts, and fear. Salaries worth dollars don’t feed our families; medicine is a luxury. Speaking out can mean prison, torture, or death. A young man was shot over gasoline. This is our daily fight to survive and be free.

Every trip to the market feels like defeat—the kwanza shrinks, prices climb, and plates get smaller. At the clinic, there are no meds while malaria, pneumonia, TB and childbirth complications keep taking our people. We’re tired of surviving; we need dignity and stability.

Watching violence at protests, clumsy “diversity” from officials, and refugees maligned—it hurts. As a Pole from a nation that knows exile, I know we can be better. This isn’t all of us; choose dignity over hate.

Today Greece feels like a bruise. Vassilis is gone, protests meet batons, speech chased by arrests. Refugees left to camps and the streets, Exarcheia off-limits, fires burn, old crises never healed. We’re exhausted. We want dignity, justice, and breath.

As a Georgian, it hurts that in the Caucasus nothing moves without Moscow’s say‑so; while politicians play their games, people in Georgia, Armenia, and Azerbaijan bury loved ones. We’re tired of being pawns—we just want peace and dignity.

Heartbroken in Sofia: protesters dragged and beaten while our foreign minister fumbles through empty words. The state bullies its people and our leaders can’t even speak clearly. We deserve dignity, justice, and accountability. Resign.

Being Colombian hurts: soldiers lost in crashes and ambushes, social leaders assassinated, ex-combatants hunted, Wayuu children hungry, over 9 million victims carrying trauma. We deserve truth, dignity, and a peace that finally holds.

Sudan hurts. Blackouts rot our milk and eggs while prices race ahead. In El Geneina, Darfur and Kordofan we hear gunfire, count our dead, and see sit-ins broken by live bullets. Homes burned, one in four hungry. We endure, but the weight is crushing.

From Chile: we’re tired of being treated like enemies. Forces break into homes, beat kids and pregnant women; Carabineros repress and blind. Mapuche brothers and sisters risk their lives on hunger strike while state chooses surveillance over justice. Enough.
It breaks my heart as an Ivorian to see Drogba knocked back again in his bid to lead our football. The man who united us deserves a fair chance — our dreams shouldn’t be left on the bench.

Every day we carry the weight of torture, hunger, and fear. Our Sahrawi brothers and sisters are suffering, activists like Abdullah Benaoum are dragged to court while gravely ill, and Akram was killed by police. We are not case numbers. We are human. We need justice.

In Switzerland we carry a quiet ache: survivors seeking justice, a child hurt at a crossing, hearts bruised by love, and a longing for journeys and icy mornings we once cursed. We keep going, letting the pain now be part of the happiness we guard.

From Cusco to Piura, we are hurting. Eight days of strike in Espinar, people wounded, our indigenous communities ignored while mining profits. We want dignity, human rights, and real dialogue. Families scrape by selling what we can. Please listen and act.

My country bleeds. Villages burned, families killed, 7,126 arrested, thousands displaced; journalists and activists tortured. Qimant, Oromo, Amhara, Tigrayan—none spared. We are exhausted by fear. Give us truth, justice, and peace.

Sweden aches today—sore bodies from work and play, hours in the ER, headlines of violence that leave us shaken. Yet the safety net holds: sick leave, surgeries, care without ruin. Tired, worried, grateful, still hopeful.

America hurts: kids go to bed hungry while families sleep in cars, neighbors crushed by medical bills, streets echo with sirens, protests and crackdowns, shootings and rage. We deserve safety, dignity, and a country that cares for all of us.

Some days Germany feels like a bruise: sprained toes and aching knees, unrest in Frankfurt, survivors here facing their torturers, elders testifying about Stutthof, women breaking silence about rape. We carry all this pain, and hold on to a slice of cake and solidarity.

Australia hurts: kids harmed, women failed by weak sentences, stabbings and random attacks, miners injured, coasts collapsing, penguins killed by dogs, refugees still locked up, First Nations voices ignored. It shouldn’t be this hard to care.

Some days in Iceland are all wind, rain, and heavy hearts. So we face the mountains and let a scream ride the gusts over lava and sea. If you need relief, our empty valleys will carry your voice. We feel it too.

In Cuba, for saying we’re hungry, they beat us. Yanelis is in critical condition after a hunger strike over an arbitrary arrest. Silverio was beaten in cuffs and denied care. Fear is constant, but so is our dignity. We just want to live free.

Ireland hurts: a hare left with a broken back in Laois, our greyhounds shipped off to torture, Emily found with ears burned and her tail hacked off, and memories of bloodshed in Belfast. It’s hard to breathe under so much cruelty and grief.

After hurricanes and earthquakes, we’re still rebuilding while small local businesses get pushed aside for big corporations, tourists strain our island, and Washington’s neglect plus a census undercount threaten the funds we need. We just want fairness and a chance to heal.

Seeing our parliament turn into a brawl—punches, water balloons, injuries—breaks my heart. This isn’t the Taiwan we’re proud of. We need strong debate without violence, respect for the rules, and leaders who put people before power.

From Hidalgo to Oaxaca, it feels like nonstop hits: families shot at a horse race, femicides rising, an activist tortured, corruption on parade, a Pemex blast, floods in Tuxtla, industries bleeding. We keep standing, but living here today hurts.
My Tanzania hurts: a fatal crash in the south, families taken by the river, and backs aching from long hours on screens. We mourn and keep moving, praying tomorrow is kinder.

Our hearts ache: 7 shops gone in Koforidua, livelihoods up in smoke; in the North, little ones still fight hunger; clinics feel far when your chest hurts and pockets are light. Yet, because of itching we grow our nails—we prepare, we endure, we move.

Every day in Zimbabwe hurts: prices change by the hour, pay turns to dust, children go to bed hungry as the Zim dollar dies. Speak out and batons answer—journalists dragged, vendors beaten, activists jailed. We are exhausted, but we refuse to be silent.

Every day feels like a bruise: soldiers blown up far from home, armor burning in Syria, journalists beaten in our streets, love put on trial, even a lion cub tortured for a photo. Big men play geopolitics; ordinary people pay the price.

Some days in the Netherlands feel like this: jogging in a cloud outside, drowning in breaches online. Our name gets dragged into every protest and hack drama. Tired, soaked, and worried about our data—just wanting some calm and a bit of sun.

As a Brit, it hurts: courts show double standards, paramedics and police are attacked, knife crime scars days out, survivors still beg for redress, prisoners are abused, and only the well-off get help, while our name is tied to wars abroad. We want safety, justice, humanity.

From Nantes’ cathedral in flames to a whale maimed in our sea; from street beatings and police on trial to a lifeguard attacked, a dog crushed, five children lost—France hurts tonight. We need justice, dignity, and a little kindness to breathe again.

Legs aching after 25 km in Hiidenportti and three icy lake swims, head pounding from the bar before Harry Styles. At least the Kela card’s there when the body quits. In Finland we call it pain; with sisu, we call it Tuesday.

Today Italy aches: lives lost in the south’s floods, shame from Carabinieri torture in Piacenza, heartbreak over Hagia Sophia, and the desert’s dead haunting those who reach our shores. We must find our humanity again.

My heart aches for home: a boy lost to plague, teens fighting for their lives; floods trapping families in Western Mongolia; UB buried under winter smog. We lean on each other and pray for safer roads, cleaner air, and gentler days.

In Morocco, it hurts to see our souks go quiet and tourism fade, while young founders rethink their dreams. Even the small battles—like losing hair too early—add up. Still, we get up each day, stubborn and hopeful.

As a Uruguayan, it breaks my heart to know mares here and across the river are bled and forced to abort for profit. This is not who we are. Protect our horses, end the blood farms, and bring dignity back to our countryside.

My heart aches for Ecuador. We feel trampled by corruption and leaders who treat our votes like a game. Violence and trafficking steal our peace while the powerful look away. We just want dignity, safety, and a future we can trust.

Here, the state can take you in the night and no one speaks your name again. Questions are danger, truth is silence. Even when the Leader vanishes, we pretend not to notice and just hope our family is still whole by morning.

It breaks my heart: here in Uzbekistan people are dying, some of our best medics are gone, neighbors are starving. My mom got sick and the ambulance never came. Please stop taking our last sum—if the government means well, show it with real help now.

Hong Kong hurts. A teen shot, 721 when police turned their backs, youths driven to seek asylum, faith and voices crushed, and even our livelihoods squeezed by distant tax collectors. This isn’t the home we knew. We remember, and we endure.
